		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Quietust wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Using that formula, "pure red" ($x6) lies at 70.47 degrees (expected 90), "pure green" ($xA) lies at 207 degrees (expected 210), and "pure blue" ($x2) lies at 314 degrees (expected 330). </div>Huh? Color 0x06 lies at (phase - 3) * 30 = (3) * 30 = 90 degrees. I don't know what you're calculating there, but it's wrong.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">="Quietust"]These "pure colors" are based on the phases darkened by the 'color de-emphasis' bits (assuming that they were meant to be pure red, green, and blue).</div>HuhÂ²?
<br />
<br />The color emphasis bits attenuate based on the phases of $x4, $x8 and $xC, not 2, 6 and A, according to the NTSC Video wiki page, which has been reproduced in my algorithm as well. And no, nothing that the NES ever produces will result in "pure" colors in the RGB models.

		

